    "7_layer_split_ylong_vs_tokio_vs_libcurl": {
      "answer": "The trace does not support blaming HTTP response polling or the OpenSSL wrapper: ylong_base and tokio_base both have exactly 2 response polls and 1 client-level pending per request, and the measured window has the same 64/64 inner/outer TLS pending shape. The ylong-specific evidence is in runtime scheduling/parking: worker migration, strong park/steal correlation, and strace syscall shape. Relative to libcurl, recvfrom/sendto counts are similar while epoll_wait/futex/clock_nanosleep/sched_yield are much higher in ylong. Thus S9C should target runtime scheduling/readiness churn only if it preserves TLS/HTTP semantics and improves CPU/RSS without hurting p95.",
